As soon as I got off of my flight at SFO and stepped into J.Q.'s car, we headed on over to the Tenderloin so that I could get some Brenda's! I was really looking forward to it since the reviews made this place sound really awesome and it did not disappoint. It was definitely one of the best meals that I had in SF :) When you walk in, there's a chalkboard for you to write down your name and how many people are in your party. Luckily a table opened up right as I was writing down our information--parties of 2 definitely get seated the fastest here. The restaurant can feel a little claustrophobic despite its tall ceiling because there are so many people crowded together (and the tables are so small... at least to me), but at least you know they're trying to accomodate as many people as they can! We started off with their Sweet Watermelon House Tea. It was very refreshing and I loved that there were thin slices of watermelon in it. We couldn't make up our minds on which beignets we wanted to try, since they all sounded so good, so we got the Beignet Flight so we could try all of them! The Plain Beignet (for the die-hard traditionalist) was exactly what it's called and shows that this place really knows how to make beignets. I really liked the Crawfish Beignet: spiced with cayenne, scallions & cheddar. The Granny Smith Apple one (sweetened with cinnamon honey butter) was also great--pretty much like an apple pie. My least favourite was the Chocolate one (filled with molten Ghirardelli chocolate). I found the chocolate to be overpowering, but I think I'm alone in that opinion since JQ loved it. For our entrees, JQ got the Grillades & Grits: beef cutlets braised in spicy creole gravy, served with grits & two eggs any style, plus cream biscuit or toast. I wanted to try this amazing biscuit that everyone was talking about, so she shared her biscuit with me. It was good, but not the best thing ever as other Yelpers had said (maybe it was overhyped for me). She loved her dish even though she ended up being too full to finish the entire thing. Weaksauce. I got the Shrimp & Grits: sautéed shrimp, cheddar grits, spicy tomato-bacon gravy. It was so good. The cheddar grits were so creamy and delicious and paired perfectly with the shrimp and gravy. And I ate my entire plate clean. So full but so worth it :) Service was good--friendly and fast--so our meal here was a complete success. They also have two unisex bathrooms here for customers.

My first experience with soul food and I thoroughly enjoyed it! The restaurant is located in the heart of the tenderloin and the interior provides a very classy yet comfort vibe. Once seated, you are given a small dish of black eyed beans which are lightly crisped and seasoning with spices, a very nice "small bite" to have prior to meal. We ended up ordering the fried chicken and collard greens, BBQ pork ribs with Mac and cheese, gumbo, and the beignet platter. The fried chicken was cooked perfectly with just the right amount of crispiness and coating and the chicken was so moist. The BBQ ribs were very flavorful but wasn't my favorite because I felt it was slightly rich. The Mac and cheese was on point, just the right amount of cheese and portion was good to complement the ribs. The gumbo? amazing! Just the right amount of rice and the soup was nice and thick with bold flavors that really scream gumbo. We ended the meal with the beignet platter which consisted of all the beignets they serve: original, Granny Smith apples, and Ghirardelli chocolate. Our favorite was definitely the chocolate, the beignets were light, but not too sweet and the filling to dough ratio was portioned very well. Definitely enjoyed first soul food experience. Highly recommend coming here for those who want to try soul food for the first time!

It was a awesome experience when i visited Brenda's French Soul Food with my family.the food was amazing.Staff was very good. I highly recommend this restaurant.

    Went for brunch on a Sunday. Reached there at 2 pm and had to wait for 20 mins for our party of 4. Tip: Best to come for late lunch (around 2.30 - 3 pm) to avoid the long waiting.

    Favorites:
    Get their watermelon ice tea, very refreshing and light.

    1. Crawfish Beignets  - We ordered the beignet flight ($9.50) which had a sample of each - crawfish, chocolate filled, apple filled and plain beignet. Personally not a huge fan of the sweet beignets. Crawfish is handsdown the best, with dusted cayenne pepper on top!!

    2. Shrimp and grits ($12) - with a layer of cheddar cheese on top, delish!!!! Perfectly seasoned creamy delishiouness with a little tangy-sweet sauce on top.  

    3. Catfish Benedict ($13) with hash/grits on the side - Huge portions, great taste and the biscuit was soo crunchy.

    Price: Food is priced reasonable. Total comes to $15 - $20 per person. As good as it gets!!
    Ambiance: clean and modern.
    Parking: Street parking, but easy to get one around.
